{"meta":{"domain":"subjects","kid":"5223","authors":[{"fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre","id":"6"}],"title":"","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:40 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:40 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"body":"<p class=\"Paragraph\">Tibetan has no specific verb mood to express the conditional. The conditional is formed by adding the particle <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ན་</span> “if” to the verb in the subordinate clause or to its auxiliary. The particle <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ན་</span> is combined with auxiliaries in the case of <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཡོད་ན་</span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འདུག་ན་</span>, and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཡིན་ན་</span>, but the following combinations are incorrect: *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རེད་ན་</span> and *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཡོད་རེད་ན་</span>.</p> <p class=\"Paragraph\">The protasis (the “if” clause) may be preceded by the expression <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">གལ་སྲིད་</span>. There are basically three types of constructions, corresponding respectively to the present, past, and “future” conditional.</p> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><strong>The present conditional</strong> expresses a possibility that has not occurred, but that remains a possibility at the time the statement is made; or else a pure hypothesis, about the likelihood of which the statement has nothing to say. In this case the verb in the subordinate clause appears in the past tense optionally followed by the past auxiliary <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">པ་ཡིན་<a href=\"#_ftn1\"></a></span><a href=\"#_ftn1\">[1]</a> and the main clause verb is in the future tense. The structure may be represented as follows:</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">གལ་སྲིད་</span> […] Verb (past) + <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ན་</span> […], Verb + Auxiliary (future)</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">གལ་སྲིད་</span> […] Verb (past) + <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">པ་ཡིན་ན་</span> […], Verb + Auxiliary (future)</li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">These constructions, which translate both the conditional and indicative moods of English, are by far the most commonly used in Tibetan to formulate conditionals. They are also sometimes used to express past and future conditionals.</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྱ་རིལ་ཚང་མ་བཟས་ན་གྲོད་ཁོག་ན་གི་རེད།</span> “If he ate all the sweets, he would have a stomach ache.”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྱི་རིལ་ཚང་མ་བཟས་པ་ཡིན་ན་གྲོད་ཁོག་ན་གི་རེད།</span> “If he ate all the sweets, he would have a stomach ache.”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">སྒམ་ལ་སྒོ་ལྕགས་བརྒྱབ་ན་ཅ་ལག་བརླག་གི་མ་རེད།</span> “If you close the box with a padlock, the things won’t be lost.” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁྱེད་རང་གིས་མོ་ཊ་བཙོང་ན་ངས་ཉོ་གི་ཡིན།</span> “If you were to sell your car, I’d buy it.”</li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">On the other hand, the present conditional is often used to translate polite requests with the verb “can” or “may” (literally: would it be all right if…).</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འདི་འདྲས་བྱས་ན་འགྲིག་གི་རེད་པས།</span> “May I do that?”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁྱེད་རང་དོ་དགོངས་འདིར་གཟིམ་ན་འགྲིག་གི་རེད།</span> “You can sleep here tonight.”</li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Finally, there is another construction involving the present conditional: The conditional subordinate is followed by the perfect auxiliary.</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"\\\">གལ་སྲིད་</span> […] Verb (past) + <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཡོད་ན་</span> […], Verb + Auxiliary (future)</li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">The meaning differs from the first two constructions only in terms of verb aspect:</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྱི་རིལ་ཚང་མ་བཟས་ཡོད་ན་གྲོད་ཁོག་ན་གི་རེད།</span> “If he has eaten all the sweets, he will have a stomach ache.”</li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><strong>The past conditional</strong> expresses a possibility that could be envisaged in the past, but that did not actually occur. The verb in the subordinate clause is usually in the past tense-aspect (perfect or perfective); the main verb is usually in the past and is followed by the perfect auxiliary or auxiliaries of probability.<a href=\"#_ftn2\">[2]</a></p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">གལ་སྲིད་</span> […] Verb (past) + <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཡོད་ན་</span> […] Verb + <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཡོད་རེད་</span> / <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">པ་ཡོད་</span></li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">གལ་སྲིད་</span> […] Verb (past) + <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">པ་ཡིན་ན་</span> […] Verb + <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཡོད་རེད་</span> / <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">པ་ཡོད་</span></li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">The following example demonstrates this:</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྱི་རིལ་ཚང་མ་བཟས་ཡོད་ན་གྲོད་ཁོག་ན་ཡོད་རེད།</span> “If (he) had eaten all the sweets, he would have had a stomach ache.”</li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">The perfective is also sometimes used:</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྱི་རིལ་ཚང་མ་བཟས་པ་ཡིན་ན་གྲོད་ཁོག་ན་ཡོད་རེད།</span> <em>idem</em>.</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">སྒམ་ལ་སྒོ་ལྕགས་བརྒྱབ་ཡོད་ན་ཅ་ལག་བརླག་ཡོད་མ་རེད།</span> “If the box had been padlocked, the things wouldn’t have been lost.”</li> <li>Or: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">སྒམ་ལ་སྒོ་ལྕགས་བརྒྱབ་ཡོད་ན་ཅ་ལག་བརླག་པ་མེད།</span> <em>idem</em>.</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁྱེད་རང་གིས་མོ་ཏ་བཙོང་ཡོད་ན་ངས་ཉོས་ཡོད་རེད།</span> “If you’d sold your car, I’d have bought it.”</li> <li>Or: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁྱེད་རང་གིས་མོ་ཏ་བཙོང་ཡོད་ན་ངས་ཉོས་པ་ཡོད། </span></li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><strong>The future conditional</strong> expresses a future possibility. In this case, the verbs of the subordinate and main clauses are in the future. This construction is not very commonly used, and it is usually replaced by the present conditional.</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">གལ་སྲིད་</span> […] Verb (present-future) + Auxiliary (future) + <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ན་</span> […] Verb + Auxiliary (future)</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁྱེད་རང་གིས་མོ་ཊ་ཚོང་གི་ཡིན་ན་ངས་ཉོ་གི་ཡིན།</span> “If you sell your car, I’ll buy it.” (Literally: If you will sell....)</li> </ul> <p> </p> <hr size=\"1\" /> <p><a href=\"#_ftnref1\">[1]</a> The auxiliary <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">པ་ཡིན་</span> may be used with any verb class (volitional or non-volitional), although sometimes other auxiliaries such as <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྱུང་ན་</span> or <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">སོང་ན་</span> may also be used. There is a slight difference between the two constructions: when the verb is followed by the auxiliary <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">པ་ཡིན་</span>, it can indicate a mere hypothesis, a general statement that is not linked to the ongoing situation.</p> <p><a href=\"#_ftnref2\">[2]</a> See also the entry discussing the auxiliaries <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">པ་ཡོད་</span> and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">པ་འདུག་</span>. (xxlink MST 28.3.2.)</p>","title":""}]}
